The first practical anatomy session happened on a Thursday morning in the second month of first year.

Hall D — the dissection hall — was a long, high-ceilinged room at the back of the science block that the rest of the college had a habit of walking past rather quickly. On a normal day it smelled of the anti-fungal cleaning solution that the lab assistant applied to the floor every evening. On dissection days it smelled of formaldehyde, which is a smell that does not leave a room in the way that most smells do. It gets into the ventilation, and the walls, and the clothes of everyone who works there, and it follows them down the corridor to the canteen at lunchtime, where it has the effect of significantly reducing the appetite of anyone sitting nearby.

The cadavers were under white cloth. There were sixteen of them, one for every two students.

Professor Nair, who had been teaching anatomy for more than two decades, came in at precisely nine o'clock, set her bag on the demonstration table, looked at the students assembled between the benches, and said: "Nobody faints. That is the first rule. If you feel you are going to faint, sit on the floor. Do not faint onto the table, do not faint onto your partner, and do not faint near any of the instruments. Is that understood?"

It was understood.

---

The procedure to be demonstrated was a simple surface incision along the ventral forearm, to begin the process of identifying the flexor tendons.

It was, by the standards of anatomy, a minor thing.

Adarsh had studied the procedure the night before. He had read the same three pages four times, and by the third time he was fairly confident he understood both the theory and the sequence. His hands, he had noted, were completely steady while he held his textbook. His hands had always been steady.

Professor Nair demonstrated the incision on the demonstration specimen. Clean, controlled, the scalpel moving in a single, unhesitating line. She looked up at the class. "Now with your own specimens. In your own time."

Adarsh looked at the white cloth.

He removed the cloth, folded it neatly — this was an instinct, not an instruction — and set it to one side.

He picked up the scalpel.

His hand was completely, utterly, unreasonably still. Which was odd, because inside his chest his heart was doing something that no cardiac chapter he had ever read had adequately described.

Professor Nair was moving between the benches. She reached Adarsh's bench and stopped. She looked at the scalpel in his hand. She looked at the cadaver. She looked at Adarsh.

"Whenever you are ready, doctor," she said.

She moved on to the next bench.

The words landed in Adarsh's chest and did something strange. She had called him *doctor.* He was eighteen years old. He had never performed an incision on anything more complicated than an orange, which had been part of the preparation exercise in September, and which he had, in the privacy of his room, practiced six times until the orange was fully disassembled.

Vicky was at the bench beside him. They had been paired at different specimens, but the benches were close enough for a quiet word to carry.

He did not look at Vicky. He did not want Vicky to know his hand was not moving.

"He is not going anywhere," Vicky said quietly. Not looking at him. Looking at his own specimen. His voice was exactly the tone of someone observing something mildly interesting about the weather. "Take your time."

It was technically the wrong thing to say. Pathologically speaking. A cadaver does not, in fact, require time to be respected. The professor would not have said it. The textbook did not contain this instruction.

Adarsh made the incision.

It was not perfect. It was three millimetres off the ideal line, which Adarsh knew because he had memorized where the ideal line was. But it was clean, and it was controlled, and it was done.

His hand was shaking by the time he put the scalpel down. Not the way it shakes when you are frightened. The way it shakes when you have done something you were not sure you could do, and the body's own reaction to this fact arrives only after the thing is finished.

He did not tell Vicky the hand was shaking. He kept it below the bench edge and waited for it to stop.

Professor Nair came back around. She looked at Adarsh's work, made a small sound of evaluation, and said: "Continue."

---

That evening in the room, Adarsh asked Vicky how he did it.

"Did what?" Vicky said. He was reviewing his notes.

"Stayed calm. In there."

Vicky looked up. He thought about the question for a moment with genuine consideration, in the way he thought about all questions — not as though the answer was obvious, but as though it deserved to be found rather than given.

"I was not calm," he said.

Adarsh looked at him.

"I just didn't want to watch you embarrass yourself," Vicky said. He went back to his notes. "It is very distracting when the person beside you is embarrassed. It affects concentration."

Adarsh was silent for a moment.

"That is an extremely selfish reason," he said.

"Yes," Vicky said, without any particular remorse.

---

Adarsh became, over the course of four years, one of the better anatomy students in the batch. His incisions were precise. His notes were thorough. He never again froze before a procedure.

He never quite forgot what had unfrozen him that first time. A voice from the next bench saying *he is not going anywhere, take your time* — a technically incorrect statement delivered in the tone of someone discussing the weather — which had the effect of reminding him, at exactly the right moment, that the person beside him was not watching to see if he failed.

He thought, sometimes, that this was the most useful thing anyone had ever said to him in a professional context.

He also thought that Vicky would have been an extraordinary doctor. He kept this thought to himself, because some thoughts are sadder when spoken.

